query <- paste("SELECT * FROM public_cases_fc",
               "WHERE service_name = 'Abandoned Vehicle'")

abandoned <- get_carto(query, format = "csv") %>%
  subset(select = -c(the_geom, cartodb_id, the_geom_webmercator))

abandonedsf <- abandoned %>% filter(!lon %>% is.na()) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon","lat"),crs = 'NAD83') %>% st_crop(y = st_bbox(phltract)) %>% 
  st_transform(crs = 2272) %>% 
  mutate(year = requested_datetime %>% as.Date() %>% year())



ab2017 <- abandonedsf %>% filter(year == 2017) %>% mutate(Legend = 'abandoned_vehicles') %>% dplyr::select(Legend)

This geospatial prediction model attempts to predict the latent risk of abandoned vehicles in Philadelphia, PA. Because a vehicle being abandoned is a relatively rare event, and can take place anywhere, being able to predict the likelihood of a vehicle being abandoned everywhere is quite powerful.

The target variable in the model is a count of abandoned vehicle 311 reports within a set unit of space. As the data set is crowd-sourced from user submissions, it is not a perfect proxy for actual abandoned vehicles, as some vehicles go unreported and a single instance of an abandoned vehicle can receive multiple reports.

Reports to 311 face selection bias for numerous reasons. Instances of abandoned vehicles could be not reported if they are in an location people rarely observe, or if those that do observe the vehicles don’t use 311 or know an abandoned vehicle is a reportable offence. Furthermore, trust in the 311 system wains when city agencies are slow to respond to reports.

Due to the data being crowd-sourced and not recorded by a city agency, selection bias compounding due to the agency’s resource allocation is not a factor. Still, being able to predict where the events will occur will be helpful for city agencies in cleanup and surveillance.

The risk factors we include in the fishnet are:

  • Amount of Illegal Dumping 311 reports in 2017.
  • Number of individual trees recorded in the Parks and Rec tree inventory.
  • Amount of vacant lot land uses.
  • Distance to nearest fire station.
  • Distance to nearest SEPTA bus line.

We also bring in neighborhood and police district boundaries for spatial LOGO analysis later.

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)
final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(
    as.data.frame(localmoran(final_net$abandoned_vehicles, final_net.weights)),
    as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(ab_vehicle_count = abandoned_vehicles, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.005, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <-

By running Local Moran’s I tests of our dependent variables see highly significant clustering of abandoned vehicles in many neighborhoods in Philly.

correlation.long <-

To build my model, I started only regressing Abandoned Vehicles on Illegal Dumping, which resulted with a MAE of 0.25, indicating on average, the error between the predicted amount of Abandoned Vehicles and the actual amount in each grid cell is 0.25. As I iteratively added more predictors, each added little accuracy, dropping MAE by 0.01. When I combined all variables, MAE decreases to 0.22. As the average amount of Abandoned Vehicles in each cell is 1.21, this amount of error is substantial.

It makes sense that Illegal Dumping is the most predictive risk factor, as they are from the same data set and are a similar phenomenon to Abandoned Vehicles. However, I am hesitant to draw more risk factors from the Philly311 data set as they will be subject to the same biases as these variables.

Using spatial LOGO cross validation, for both neighborhood and police district grouping resulted in higher MAE’s, suprisingly.

tracts18 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E"), 
          year = 2018, state='PA', county='Philadelphia', geometry=T, progress_bar = FALSE) %>%
  st_transform(2272)  %>% 
  dplyr::select(variable, estimate, GEOID) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority_White", "Majority_Non_White")) %>%
  .[nhoods,]

reg.summary %>% 
  filter(str_detect(Regression, "All")) %>%
  st_centroid() %>%
  st_join(tracts18) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(Regression, raceContext) %>%
  summarize(mean.Error = mean(Error, na.rm = T)) %>%
  spread(raceContext, mean.Error) %>%
  kable(caption = "Mean Error by neighborhood racial context") %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)

Unfortunately, our model is not very generalizable by race. By comparing Mean Errors between census tracts that are majority-white and majority non-white, we see that white tracts over predict the amount of abandoned vehicles, and vice-versa.

This bar graph compares the effectiveness of our risk prediction models to a business-as-usual kernel density approach. As the kernel density out predicts our model at the highest two risk levels, we unfortunately cannot say that our model is better than the normal approach.

Conclusion

While the model I created could allocate resources better than a random deployment, it does not out-predict the traditional kernel density approach, and thus I would not recommend it to be used to prevent vehicle abandonments. As a vehicle being abandoned is a fairly inconspicuous event, being able to catch perpetrators in the act is harder than for other crimes. The type of modeling done here could be helpful in placing surveillance cameras, but ultimate the best way to have abandoned vehicles reported is through community input.

Abandoned vehicles are nuisance to the neighborhoods they are in, and their timely removal is important. Being able to track where they will occur is important keeping the streets clean.
